A quick Lua version:<p><pre><code>    do
      local mt = {
        __index = function(t, k)
          t[k] = tree()
          return t[k]
        end
      }

      function tree()
        return setmetatable({}, mt)
      end
    end

    t = tree()
    t.foo.bar = 'foobar'</code></pre>

> I've wanted something like that in Python at different times... thanks!<p>Python's auto-vivification doens't allow Perl's hap hazard auto-vivification. Perl allows you to say:<p><pre><code>    my $foo = {};
    $foo->{'blah'}[0]->{'bar'}++;
</code></pre>
And after this statement, $foo will refer a hash which has the structure as accessed in the statement.<p>I don't think this can be done for a generalized case in Python. Whether I want is a totally different question.
